quran[24]{c,v,t}:
  26,10,"When your Lord called out to Moses: [saying,] ‘Go to those wrongdoing people"
  26,11,"the people of Pharaoh. Will they not be wary [of Allah]?’"
  26,12,"He said, ‘My Lord! I fear they will impugn me"
  26,13,"and I will become upset and my tongue will fail me. So send for Aaron [to join me]"
  26,14,"Besides, they have a charge against me, and I fear they will kill me.’"
  26,15,"He said, ‘Certainly not! Let both of you go with Our signs: We will indeed be with you, hearing [everything]"
  26,16,"So approach Pharaoh and say, ‘‘We are indeed envoys of the Lord of the worlds"
  26,17,that you let the Children of Israel leave with us.’’ ’
  26,18,"He [i.e. Pharaoh] said, ‘Did we not rear you as a child among us, and did you not stay with us for years of your life"
  26,19,"Then you committed that deed of yours, and you are an ingrate.’"
  26,20,"He said, ‘I did that when I was astray"
  26,21,"So I fled from you, as I was afraid of you. Then my Lord gave me sound judgement and made me one of the apostles"
  26,22,That you have enslaved the Children of Israel—is that the favour with which you reproach me?’
  26,23,"He said, ‘And what is ‘‘the Lord of all the worlds?’’ ’"
  26,24,"He said, ‘The Lord of the heavens and the earth and whatever is between them,—should you have conviction.’"
  26,25,"He said to those who were around him, ‘Don’t you hear?!’"
  26,26,"He said, ‘Your Lord, and the Lord of your forefathers!’"
  26,27,"He said, ‘Indeed your messenger, who has been sent to you, is surely crazy!’"
  26,28,"He said, ‘The Lord of the east and the west and whatever is between them—should you exercise your reason.’"
  26,29,"He said, ‘If you take up any god other than me, I will surely make you a prisoner!’"
  26,30,"He said, ‘What if I bring you something [as an] unmistakable [proof]?’"
  26,31,"He said, ‘Then bring it, should you be truthful.’"
  26,32,"Thereat he threw down his staff, and behold, it was a manifest python"
  26,33,"Then he drew out his hand, and behold, it was white and bright to the onlookers"